pathologyNote: T1 vertebra has a well-defined pit on the left lateral aspect of the centrum just inferior to the superior costal pit. The pit measures 7.5 x 5 mm and is 4.3 mm deep. It is roughly triangular in shape with the apex of the triangle pointing dorsally. No sclerosis evident. An indentation exists in the same location on the right side. T5-T9 vertebrae have a linear series of irregularly shaped pits on their centra. The pits are midway between the superior and inferior aspects of the centrum. They appear to be the result of cortical thinning. The superior and inferior articular facets of all thoracic and lumbar are very mildly marginally lipped Two overlapping foci of bone loss are present on the auricular surface of the right ilium just posterior to the apex of the joint surface. The pits measure ~3.5 mm in diameter and are 3-4 mm deep. They are well-defined but not sclerotic. The heads of both femora seem slightly flattened in the area of the fovea capitis and are not well defined but appear as a slightly roughened area on the articular surface. A number of articular surfaces have numerous tiny pits that appear to be an artifact of preservation.

pathologyNote: Occipital tabular flattening (90° or toward anterior), pressure was centered at squamous/occipital; slight mandibular and maxillary periodontal disease as well as medium torus; hypertrophied Tuberculaum Dentale on maxillary lateral incisor; large caries in both buccal roots of tooth #3; interproximal carries on teeth #’s 6-12; #3 apical abscess drains to buccal; #12 & 14 apical abscesses drain to labial; cervical caries in #’s 4, 5, 17 & 31; occlusal cavity on #17; teeth #’s 11, 22 & 27 have diffuse horizontal bands of thin irregular and rough enamel
